  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation combating money laundering has evolved significantly over the past several decades:\n\n1. Early Developments\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970, USA)\n- First international anti-money laundering guidelines\n- Initial focus on reporting large cash transactions\n\n2. Key Milestones\n- FATF establishment (1989)\n- Increased international cooperation\n- Standardized reporting requirements\n- Enhanced customer due diligence protocols\n\n3. Modern Regulatory Frameworks\n- Enhanced Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Comprehensive beneficial ownership disclosure\n- Stricter penalties for non-compliance\n- Advanced digital transaction monitoring\n- Expanded scope beyond traditional banking\n\n4. Technological Adaptations\n- Cryptocurrency transaction tracking\n- Machine learning for suspicious activity detection\n- Cross-border information sharing mechanisms\n- Real-time transaction screening\n\n5. Recent Trends\n- Increased focus on cryptocurrency regulations\n- Enhanced sanctions enforcement\n- More aggressive penalties\n- Broader institutional accountability\n- Greater emphasis on corporate transparency\n\nThese legislative developments reflect ongoing efforts to create more robust financial crime prevention strategies, adapting to emerging technologies and sophisticated laundering techniques.\n\nThe progression demonstrates a continuous, collaborative global approach to combating financial crime.",
